<paragraph blockId="105.[151,1436,152,418]" box="[198,1298,232,258]" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">
<emphasis box="[198,330,232,257]" italics="true" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the Latin, meaning “belt, girdle,” referring to the setal pattern of tergum II.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="105.[151,1436,152,418]" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">
<emphasis box="[198,301,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species is known only from the female. It keys easily after couplet #2. The mesosoma is slightly longer than broad, with a circle of black setae on the dorsum. There is a bilobed pattern of black setae on tergum II anteriorly. The setae are contrasting yellow/orange and black. This species resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1855" box="[1320,1435,352,377]" genus="Mutilla" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="105" pageNumber="106" rank="species" species="canina">
<emphasis box="[1320,1435,352,377]" italics="true" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">D. canina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[200,314,392,417]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Dasymutilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="105" pageNumber="106" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jalisco">
<emphasis box="[200,314,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">D. jalisco</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs in having the mesosoma longer than broad.
</paragraph>
